trackedEntityTypes.description: This is a generic type class for AMR. The tracked entities are in effect a pathogen sample, and may have come from human, animal, environmental, food or feed samples. At a minimum, each instance of the AMR Entity must have an identification number. The metadata associated with the specific source of entity is captured at the tracked program level.

*SAMPLE SIZE* : This sub-section provides an overview of a sample size of Pathogens in number and Percentage tested against a particular Antibiotics. Under normal circumstances, the percentage of pathogens tested for each antibiotic is supposed to be 100% . *However* , this is not happening due to several reasons.
The Abbreviation for Antibiotics:  _AMOXWC = Amoxicillin clavulanic, AMP = Ampicillin, CHLOR = Chloramphenicol, CIPRO = Ciprofloxacin, COL = Colistin, ERTA = Ertapenem, CEFEP = Cefepime, CEFOT = Cefotaxime, CEFPO = Cefpodoxime, CEFTAZ = Ceftazidime, GENTA = Gentamicin, IMIP = Imipenem, NAL = Nalidixic acid, Sulfonamides, TETRA = Tetracycline, SULFAET = Trimethoprim/sulphamethoxazole, CEFTRX = Ceftriaxone_

*STUDY DATA: AMR ANIMAL*

The Animal AMR data presented here is based on a study conducted back in 2014. The study involved 105 farms allocated in 6 districts of _Mazabuka, Chongwe, Chibombo, Lusaka, Kabwe, Kafue._ The study focused on E.coli pathogen extracted from faecal specimen. The total of 6 antibiotics tested, thus are *Ampicillin, Cefpodoxime, Ciprofloxin, Gentamicin, Tetracycline and T/sulphamethoxazole*
ANIMAL: PATHOGENS RESISTANCE BY ANTIBIOTIC
